  "prompt": "Why is white colour only showing once in the spectrum?",
  "response": "That's a great question! The reason we see the other colors of the rainbow separated in a spectrum, but don't see a separated \"white\" band is because **white isn't a single color.**\n\nHere's the breakdown:\n\n*   **White light is a mixture:** White light, like sunlight or the light from a standard light bulb, is actually composed of all the colors of the visible spectrum combined.\n\n*   **A prism separates the colors:** When white light passes through a prism, the different wavelengths of light that make it up are bent (refracted) at slightly different angles. This causes the colors to separate and spread out, creating the spectrum we see.\n\n*   **Each color has its own wavelength:** Red light has the longest wavelength in the visible spectrum, and it bends the least. Violet light has the shortest wavelength and bends the most. The other colors fall in between.\n\n*   **Why no separate \"white\" band?** Because white light is the *combination* of all those colors, there's nothing to separate *into* white. The prism splits the white light into its constituent colors, but doesn't create a distinct band of white. If you combined all the colors of the spectrum back together, you would get white light again.\n\n**Analogy:**\n\nThink of white light like a cake made of different ingredients. The prism is like a tool that separates the cake back into flour, sugar, eggs, etc. You don't see a separate \"cake\" pile after the separation, because the \"cake\" was the combined form to begin with.\n\n**In short, the spectrum shows us the individual colors that make up white light, not a separate component called \"white.\"**\n",
